It is possible to obtain the expected result with a custom serializer, but you loose all the advantages available with the use of [`JsonTypeInfo`](https://fasterxml.github.io/jackson-annotations/javadoc/2.12/com/fasterxml/jackson/annotation/JsonTypeInfo.html) and you have to write a custom deserializer too. Anyway, you can define three simple classes like below:

~~~
public abstract class Animal {}
public class Dog extends Animal {}

@JsonSerialize(using = ZooSerializer.class)
public class Zoo {
  List&lt;Animal&gt; animals = new ArrayList&lt;&gt;();
}
~~~

Then you have to write your custom `ZooSerializer` serializer that will build your custom xml:

~~~
public class ZooSerializer extends StdSerializer&lt;Zoo&gt; {

    public ZooSerializer(Class&lt;Zoo&gt; t) {
        super(t);
    }
    
    public ZooSerializer() {
        this(null);
    }

    @Override
    public void serialize(Zoo zoo, JsonGenerator jg, SerializerProvider sp) throws IOException {
        jg.writeStartObject();
        for (Animal animal: zoo.animals) {
            jg.writeNullField(animal.getClass().getSimpleName());
        }
        jg.writeEndObject();
    }
